I"Í<p>Here we will investigate one of the methods of evaluating integrals asymptotically.</p>

<p>Suppose we had the integral</p>

<script type="math/tex; mode=display">I = \int_0^1 \frac{\sin(x)}{\epsilon^2 + x^2} dx</script>

<p>As $\epsilon\to 0$, the integral becomes logarithmically divergent. One way to simplify the problem is</p>

<script type="math/tex; mode=display">\begin{eqnarray}
\int_0^1 \frac{\sin(x)}{\epsilon^2 + x^2} dx 
\end{eqnarray}</script>
